POMPEIUS, etc. ; and the general opinion of critics has been that J ustin confounded Semo, the Sabine Hercules (Ovid Fasti vi. 21), with Simon Magus (Vales. in Euseb. Z. e.). Tillemont (II. i. 341), however, points out that 13110 inscriptions are not identical, the words and order differ- ing; that J ustin states that the statue was set up by Claudius and the Senate, whereas that to Semo was erected by a private individual; and that Augustine, who knew of the Sabine Semo (de civ. Dei xviii. 19), confirms Justin’s words (Haer. i. 6). Burton, also (Bamp. Lect. note 423 Charch Hist. p. 175, 3rd ed.), argues the impossibility of J ustin being mistaken. On the other hand, Prof. Salmon, in Dict. Olor. Bioy. iv. 682, thinks ‘the coincidence is too remarkable 130 admit of any other satisfactory explanation ² 3 and believes that J ustin was deceived by the Simonians in Rome.
